{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:29:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:29:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16295"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16295"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.1,0.14,0.05,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8986"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116076"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8986"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16295"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98072"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"8567"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116076"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe perception of taste requires a complex neural pathway beginning with receptors in the tongue and extending through multiple cranial nerves to reach processing centres in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the first central relay point for taste information?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fungiform papillae","Nucleus ambiguus","Lateral geniculate nucleus","Medial longitudinal fasciculus","Solitary nucleus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esolitary nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E serves as the initial brainstem processing centre for gustatory information. Three cranial nerves - the facial (VII), glossopharyngeal (IX), and vagus (X) - carry taste signals to this nucleus. From here, information continues to the thalamus and eventually reaches the gustatory regions of the cerebral cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungiform papillae\u003C/strong\u003E represent peripheral taste structures on the tongue surface rather than central processing stations. The \u003Cstrong\u003Enucleus ambiguus\u003C/strong\u003E coordinates motor aspects of swallowing and voice production. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral geniculate nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E processes visual rather than gustatory information, whilst the \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial longitudinal fasciculus\u003C/strong\u003E coordinates eye movements and postural responses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gustatory information travels via cranial nerves VII, IX, and X, terminating in the brainstem solitary nucleus.","Taste perception involves a pathway from the solitary nucleus through the thalamus to the gustatory cortex."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Gravina SA, Yep GL, Khan M. Human biology of taste. Ann Saudi Med. 2013 May-Jun;33(3):217-22. doi: 10.5144/0256-4947.2013.217. PMID: 23793421; PMCID: PMC6078535"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98072"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","